s, the explosive rise of car mobility has transformed street life in post-socialist cities. Whereas previously the social fabric of these cities ran on socialist modes of mobility, they are now overtaken by a culture of privately owned cars. If Cars Could Walk uses ethnographic cases studies documenting these changes in terms of street interaction, vehicles used, and the parameters of speed, maneuverability, and cultural and symbolic values. The altered reality of people’s movements, replacing public transport, bicycles and other former ‘socialist’ modes of mobility with privatized mobility reflect an evolving political and cultural imagination, which in turn shapes their current political reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutomobiles. 0aPost-communism. 0aTransportation. 0aUrban transportation. 7aTravel / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aTransport Studies, History: 20th Century to Present, Cultural Studies (General).1 aCurro, Costanza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuijzings, Ger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuijzings, Ger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGagica, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGatejel, Luminita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHotaka Roth, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaslova, Sabina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMöser, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorton, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlma, Nikolaos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular